over individuals,
state that they earn 53

00:36:09.170 --> 00:36:12.200
or some other thousand
dollars, and then rebate

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:15.530
that money-- a percentage
of that money, 15% or 20%,

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:17.210
to the Imam.

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:21.590
Then, in addition to that,
they engage in a massive amount

00:36:21.590 --> 00:36:25.970
of self-dealing through
real estate ventures,

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:32.250
through crony capitalism
at its worst, where

00:36:32.250 --> 00:36:35.490
Gulen-related construction
companies engage

00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:40.800
in no bid or low bid contracts
where the quality has just

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:42.750
been fairly shocking.

00:36:42.750 --> 00:36:45.180
And what we've
done is we've tried

00:36:45.180 --> 00:36:51.750
to work with a whole group of
American parents and teachers

00:36:51.750 --> 00:36:58.730
to bring this to
light in really the 26

00:36:58.730 --> 00:37:02.750
states in which the schools
are located, and we've been--

00:37:02.750 --> 00:37:06.890
frankly it's been very difficult
because the charter school

00:37:06.890 --> 00:37:11.960
industry in this country
is a religious totem

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:15.200
for certain people
and many Republicans,

00:37:15.200 --> 00:37:18.590
and even if you say
that we're not viewing--

00:37:18.590 --> 00:37:22.640
we're not trying to argue
pro-charter or anti-charter.

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:26.510
What we're trying to say is,
here's a bad charter that

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:27.860
needs to be addressed.

00:37:27.860 --> 00:37:31.070
Even if that's how
limited you approach it,

00:37:31.070 --> 00:37:35.390
it is very difficult
because many people simply

00:37:35.390 --> 00:37:37.940
don't want to hear
it, and this is

00:37:37.940 --> 00:37:44.600
one of the things I'm
finding in America today--

00:37:44.600 --> 00:37:50.100
is that we've really lost the
ability to hear our opponents.

00:37:50.100 --> 00:37:54.450
We've really lost
the ability to engage

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:58.080
in real meaningful dialogue.

00:37:58.080 --> 00:38:02.370
And there's a book
that just came

00:38:02.370 --> 00:38:07.380
out called "The Death of
Expertise" by a guy named

00:38:07.380 --> 00:38:09.660
Tom Nichols, and
actually there's

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:11.250
a quote in this
book that's just--

00:38:11.250 --> 00:38:14.190
I think it just sums it up.

00:38:14.190 --> 00:38:15.870
"The death of
expertise is not just

00:38:15.870 --> 00:38:17.670
a rejection of
existing knowledge.

00:38:17.670 --> 00:38:21.690
It is fundamentally a rejection
of science and dispassionate

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:24.060
rationality, which
are the foundations

00:38:24.060 --> 00:38:27.480
of modern civilization.

00:38:27.480 --> 00:38:29.520
All citizens today
believe themselves

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:32.460
to be experts on everything."

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:35.670
And it's one of-- if you'll
excuse me, for all of the good

00:38:35.670 --> 00:38:39.480
that Google has done, it is one
of the unfortunate byproducts

00:38:39.480 --> 00:38:42.420
of googling-- is
that people believe

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:45.750
that within a few minutes
of googling any subject

00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:47.400
they've mastered it.

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:50.820
And certainly one of
the problems we've faced

00:38:50.820 --> 00:38:54.720
is trying to explain
at the state level

00:38:54.720 --> 00:38:58.590
from politicians, many
of whom have received

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:01.500
significant payments
from this organization,

00:39:01.500 --> 00:39:06.400
that there's a very
serious problem in terms

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:09.400
of not only what
this organization did

00:39:09.400 --> 00:39:12.550
during the coup, but what this
organization has been doing

00:39:12.550 --> 00:39:14.710
in Turkey for many,
many years and what

00:39:14.710 --> 00:39:19.710
they appear to be intending to
do here in the United States.

00:39:19.710 --> 00:39:21.360
AUDIENCE: Really
what the prognosis

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:25.180
is for the future in terms
of corporations dealing

00:39:25.180 --> 00:39:28.620
on this governmental level-- is
it a matter of banding together

00:39:28.620 --> 00:39:32.700
to express their interest
in a confederation,

00:39:32.700 --> 00:39:36.060
or is it better just
that they each have

00:39:36.060 --> 00:39:39.030
their own, essentially,
foreign policy?

00:39:39.030 --> 00:39:41.550
ROBERT AMSTERDAM:
Well, I think it's

00:39:41.550 --> 00:39:45.120
going to be necessary
for governments

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:49.630
to once again attempt
to come together.

00:39:49.630 --> 00:39:52.320
We're going to see
the French vote.

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:56.020
We're going to see the
Brexit negotiations,

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:58.830
but I think the
Trump administration

00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:02.430
has to decide on
what its message is

00:40:02.430 --> 00:40:04.410
and who its voice is.

00:40:04.410 --> 00:40:06.600
I mean, we're in an
embarrassing scenario

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:11.340
here where the president
will say one thing

00:40:11.340 --> 00:40:17.520
to the American public, and then
a completely different message

00:40:17.520 --> 00:40:22.100
is raised in Munich
by the vice president.

00:40:22.100 --> 00:40:27.350
I mean, you can't really
run a foreign policy

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:32.420
with that many discordant
voices at the highest level.

00:40:32.420 --> 00:40:38.240
So if what happens is the
Trump administration starts

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:44.300
to veer towards a more middle
of the road historically

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:47.590
consistent American
position, you're

00:40:47.590 --> 00:40:50.380
seeing an American economy
that is starting to pick up

00:40:50.380 --> 00:40:54.850
in a major way, and
it may be possible

00:40:54.850 --> 00:40:58.750
that after some very significant
veering to-ing and fro-ing

00:40:58.750 --> 00:41:02.410
we get back on track.

00:41:02.410 --> 00:41:05.960
We renegotiate NAFTA.

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:09.620
We realize that complete
abandonment of the TPP

00:41:09.620 --> 00:41:11.360
and leaving Asia
to China may not

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:14.060
be the greatest deal
in town, and we come up

00:41:14.060 --> 00:41:17.960
with some new methodology,
some powerful series

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:21.080
of bilaterals that would
save president Trump's face

00:41:21.080 --> 00:41:24.920
and at the same time
keep us in the game.

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:30.380
This is a great country that
leads the world in technology

00:41:30.380 --> 00:41:34.670
and leads the world, until
recently, in many key sectors

00:41:34.670 --> 00:41:37.010
like environmental technology.

00:41:37.010 --> 00:41:40.160
So I think there's still a
tremendous amount of hope.

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:43.850
There isn't a necessity for
us to be negative completely,

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:47.660
but we also have to
suggest to the Democrats

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:49.700
that we don't want
to have another four

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:53.210
years of a stalemated Congress.

00:41:53.210 --> 00:41:55.240
And I think that's--

00:41:55.240 --> 00:41:58.320
the message has to be given
to both political parties

00:41:58.320 --> 00:42:00.070
that they're going to
be held accountable,

00:42:00.070 --> 00:42:06.640
and as somebody who has
been ferociously attacking

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:08.290
on the issue of
Russia, I can say

00:42:08.290 --> 00:42:15.210
that the level of
instrumentalization

00:42:15.210 --> 00:42:20.160
of this issue of the
Russia hack really has--

00:42:20.160 --> 00:42:24.210
the Democrats really
have to slow down or--

00:42:24.210 --> 00:42:27.210
forget the presumption
of innocence.

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:31.580
You do have to understand
that logically,

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:34.310
if you're sitting
here looking at what

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:36.440
happened in the election--

00:42:36.440 --> 00:42:38.420
I'm sorry, from my
perspective, and I was here

00:42:38.420 --> 00:42:39.800
for most of the time--

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:42.200
if I was going to point to
anything that might have swung

00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:44.740
the election, it
was the Democrats

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:49.700
forgetting their base, and
it was Comey and the FBI.

00:42:49.700 --> 00:42:52.220
And I think a lot of questions
have to be asked of Comey.

00:42:52.220 --> 00:42:55.280
If he was aware of
this Russia stuff,

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:58.040
it sounds far more
relevant than reopening

00:42:58.040 --> 00:43:02.420
Hillary to have at least opened
an investigation about that.

00:43:02.420 --> 00:43:06.740
And it seems shocking to me, as
does the Obama administration's

00:43:06.740 --> 00:43:07.880
reaction.

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:11.480
Once again, when you talk
about foreign policy,

00:43:11.480 --> 00:43:13.250
the Obama
administration does not

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:18.260
get five stars, and this issue
of how they've handled Russia--

00:43:18.260 --> 00:43:21.530
they did to Russia what
Trump did to Mexico.

00:43:21.530 --> 00:43:25.190
Obama insulted
Russia unnecessarily.

00:43:25.190 --> 00:43:29.960
There was no reason to call it
a second rate regional power

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:35.300
unless what you want to do is
just pour gasoline on a fire.

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:40.220
There's so much that a president
can do by his presentation,

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:45.080
by his words, by his conduct to
show respect to other nations,

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:49.880
and President Obama really
dropped the ball with respect

00:43:49.880 --> 00:43:52.100
to Russia--

00:43:52.100 --> 00:43:54.470
and to be fair, has
dropped the ball in respect

00:43:54.470 --> 00:43:59.090
to a number of other
areas, like Syria--

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:03.980
and has left has left Trump
with some real difficulties.

00:44:03.980 --> 00:44:08.500
And the fact is about
Russia they don't

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:11.050
have to be a mortal enemy.

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:12.370
There's no reason for it.

00:44:12.370 --> 00:44:15.670
I think to that
extent Trump is right.

00:44:15.670 --> 00:44:19.090
Russia has to clean up its
act, and at the same time,

00:44:19.090 --> 00:44:21.880
some form of face saver
can be negotiated.

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:29.290
The real hard point is what are
we going to do about Crimea.

00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:32.390
How is Crimea to be resolved?

00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:37.310
That is one of the key points
for European integrity.

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:39.440
As well as, obviously,
the expansion

00:44:39.440 --> 00:44:41.040
that's going on
in eastern Ukraine

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.940
is incredibly threatening,
but one believes

00:44:43.940 --> 00:44:45.800
that can be more controlled.

00:44:45.800 --> 00:44:49.670
I think from a Putin
standpoint Crimea is probably

00:44:49.670 --> 00:44:53.450
entering the realm of
the non-negotiable,

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:56.390
and that presents a real
problem because it's

00:44:56.390 --> 00:44:59.180
around Crimea and
eastern Ukraine

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:03.710
that the entire sanctions
morass is based.

00:45:03.710 --> 00:45:05.660
AUDIENCE: You've
talked a lot about what

00:45:05.660 --> 00:45:08.675
the corporations can do and what
the federal government can do.

00:45:08.675 --> 00:45:10.970
Do you have a charge
for the individual?

00:45:10.970 --> 00:45:15.909
Is there something that you
feel like the individual can do?

00:45:15.909 --> 00:45:17.450
ROBERT AMSTERDAM:
Yeah, I'll tell you

00:45:17.450 --> 00:45:25.040
I think that one of the things
the last election demonstrated

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:29.690
very significantly is that
individuals can do a lot.

00:45:29.690 --> 00:45:32.060
The last election
demonstrated it.

00:45:32.060 --> 00:45:34.850
The march on Washington
the day after the inaugural

00:45:34.850 --> 00:45:36.650
demonstrated it,
even though there

00:45:36.650 --> 00:45:39.590
were far fewer people at
the march on Washington

00:45:39.590 --> 00:45:40.580
than at the inaugural.

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:43.840
We all know that.

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:47.560
That was very
powerful, and I think

00:45:47.560 --> 00:45:50.260
with the assistance
of the internet,

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:53.020
with the assistance
of media harnessing

00:45:53.020 --> 00:45:56.920
technology a tremendous
amount can be done.

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:00.460
In fact, arguably
the Trump team did

00:46:00.460 --> 00:46:04.990
a tremendous amount by
harnessing digital technology,

00:46:04.990 --> 00:46:08.440
and the same team that
did Trump did Brexit.

00:46:08.440 --> 00:46:12.730
And it's led to a lot of very
powerful and obviously somewhat

00:46:12.730 --> 00:46:13.522
difficult outcomes.

00:46:13.522 --> 00:46:15.479
SPEAKER: Well, thank you
very much for speaking

00:46:15.479 --> 00:46:16.160
with us today.

00:46:16.160 --> 00:46:19.180
We'll have a link to your
blog and site in our video,

00:46:19.180 --> 00:46:22.094
as well, for our viewers,
and thanks for stopping by.

00:46:22.094 --> 00:46:23.260
ROBERT AMSTERDAM: Thank you.

